text=!!HowTo for Flashing your Bios on a Server running Linux%0a%0aNew Eric Auer Link: http://www.auersoft.eu/soft/by-others/%0a%0a!!!5 Steps to your bootable USB-Drive so you can flash your Bios%0a# Download [[http://www.coli.uni-saarland.de/~eric/makebootfat-1.5.tgz | Makebootfat with the Eric Auer Patch]], [[http://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=5109 | Command.com]] (in the download Link it is called FreeCOM), [[http://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=5109 | Kernel.sys]], [[http://www.japheth.de/Download/Himem330.ZIP | Himemx.exe]] (Version 3.32).%0a# Create a directory in /tmp where you have to place, a) all your BIOS Upgrade files b) himemx.exe, c) command.com d) kernel.sys%0a# Change to the directory where you untared makebootfat with Eric Auers Patch. You will have FreeDOS and mbr.bin in that directory.%0a# Run this command a)  "sudo makebootfat -v -H 64 -l -D -3 [[http://www.ibiblio.org/pub/micro/pc-stuff/freedos/files/distributions/1.0/pkgs/kernels.zip | freedos-fat32lba.bin]] -E 255 -m [[http://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/utils/boot/syslinux/ | mbrfat.bin]] -o /dev/sdb /tmp/directory_you_created_with_all_the_files_from_step_one". b) if the Stick is totally new and has _not_ been toyed around with, try this: "sudo makebootfat -v -l -P -2 freedos-fat16.bin -3 freedos-fat32lba.bin -E 255 -o /dev/sdb /tmp/directory_you_created_with_all_the_files_from_step_one".%0a# If you get a strange command \P not found grab the config.sys and autoexec.bat from [[http://sourceforge.net/projects/freedos/files/ | here]]%0a# If you get a "E:256" error it is possible that you Bios does not support highmem. Switch off Highmem and command.com should work. Also see [[http://fd-doc.sourceforge.net/faq/cgi-bin/viewfaq.cgi?faq=Installing_FreeDOS/269 | this thread]].%0a# Boot from USB.%0a%0a!!!Links%0a* http://www.linuxinsight.com/how-to-flash-motherboard-bios-from-linux-no-dos-windows-no-floppy-drive.html (did not work for me)%0a* http://ben.franske.com/blogs/2007/08/21/booting_dos_from_a_usb_flash_drive (worked for me with some extra steps)%0a* http://www.stilen.com/notes/usb_dos_boot.txt (if you follow this HowTo then make sure to make the first cylinder - of the first partition - from 1-214 and nothing else).%0a%0a!!!Software%0a* http://rugxulo.googlepages.com/ (FreeDOS)%0a* http://www.fdos.org/bootdisks/autogen/FDOEM.144.gz (old)%0a* http://freedos.svn.sourceforge.net/viewvc/freedos/kernel/trunk/boot/ (this file is included in the Patch of Eric Auer).%0a%0a!!!Finding out your Bios-Version without doing a reboot%0a* dmidecode -s bios-version%0a%0a!!!HP Drive Key Boot Utility%0a* By using this [[http://h20000.www2.hp.com/bizsupport/TechSupport/SoftwareDescription.jsp?lang=en&cc=US&swItem=MTX-UNITY-I23839# | HP utility]] I found out that my FileSystem has to be FAT16 (LBA)! Also the first cylinder has to start at 1 and end somewhere at 214. Everything else did not work for my [[http://www.victorinox.ch/index.cfm?site=victorinox.ch&page=157&lang=D | 2GB Victorinox USB-Stick]].%0a* Fdisk partition table looked like this afterwards:%0aAttach:fdisk_bios_usb_flash_partition_table.jpg\\%0a* Make sure you have FAT on that USB-stick and _not_ a FAT32.%0a%0a!!!Input by Eric Auer%0a* Use mtools to modify contents of USB and floppy images.%0a* dd count=8000 if=/dev/zero of=/tmp/floppy ; mkdosfs /tmp/floppy is probably ambiguous. Better use for example bs=1024 count=2880 instead of using only count. If size is higher, better not call the file "floppy" to avoid confusing readers :-).%0a* Attach:von_eric_auer_6.6.2008.txt%0a* Attach:von_eric_auer_9.6.2008.txt%0a%0a!!!Eric Auer's way[[#AuersWay]]%0a# sudo ~/sys-freedos.pl --lba --drive=255 --disk=/dev/sdb1 http://www.coli.uni-saarland.de/~eric/stuff/soft/specials/sys-freedos-linux.zip - new link of Eric Auer: http://www.auersoft.eu/soft/by-others/%0a# sudo mcopy btc-boot/*.* c: http://www.coli.uni-saarland.de/~eric/btc-boot.zip%0a# If you want Himem: http://www.japheth.de/Jemm.html
